│ 12359 #. ``sge``: signed greater or equal                                     │
│ 12360 #. ``slt``: signed less than                                            │
│ 12361 #. ``sle``: signed less or equal                                        │
│ 12362                                                                         │
│ 12363 The remaining two arguments must be :ref:`integer <t_integer>` or       │
│ 12364 :ref:`pointer <t_pointer>` or integer :ref:`vector <t_vector>` typed.   │
│ They                                                                          │
│ 12365 must also be identical types.                                           │
│ 12366                                                                         │
│ 12367 Semantics:                                                              │
│ 12368 """"""""""                                                              │
│ 12369                                                                         │
│ 12370 The '``icmp``' compares ``op1`` and ``op2`` according to the condition  │
│ 12371 code given as ``cond``. The comparison performed always yields either   │
│ an                                                                            │
│ 12372 :ref:`i1 <t_integer>` or vector of ``i1`` result, as follows:           │
│ 12373                                                                         │
│ 12374 .. _icmp_md_cc_sem:                                                     │
│ 12375                                                                         │
│ 12376 #. ``eq``: yields ``true`` if the operands are equal, ``false``         │
│ 12377    otherwise. No sign interpretation is necessary or performed.         │
│ 12378 #. ``ne``: yields ``true`` if the operands are unequal, ``false``       │
│ 12379    otherwise. No sign interpretation is necessary or performed.         │
│ 12380 #. ``ugt``: interprets the operands as unsigned values and yields       │
│ 12381    ``true`` if ``op1`` is greater than ``op2``.                         │
│ 12382 #. ``uge``: interprets the operands as unsigned values and yields       │
│ 12383    ``true`` if ``op1`` is greater than or equal to ``op2``.             │
│ 12384 #. ``ult``: interprets the operands as unsigned values and yields       │
│ 12385    ``true`` if ``op1`` is less than ``op2``.                            │
│ 12386 #. ``ule``: interprets the operands as unsigned values and yields       │
│ 12387    ``true`` if ``op1`` is less than or equal to ``op2``.                │
│ 12388 #. ``sgt``: interprets the operands as signed values and yields         │
│ ``true``                                                                      │
│ 12389    if ``op1`` is greater than ``op2``.                                  │
│ 12390 #. ``sge``: interprets the operands as signed values and yields         │
│ ``true``                                                                      │
│ 12391    if ``op1`` is greater than or equal to ``op2``.                      │
│ 12392 #. ``slt``: interprets the operands as signed values and yields         │
│ ``true``                                                                      │
│ 12393    if ``op1`` is less than ``op2``.                                     │
│ 12394 #. ``sle``: interprets the operands as signed values and yields         │
│ ``true``                                                                      │
│ 12395    if ``op1`` is less than or equal to ``op2``.                         │
│ 12396                                                                         │
│ 12397 If the operands are :ref:`pointer <t_pointer>` typed, the pointer       │
│ values                                                                        │
│ 12398 are compared as if they were integers.                                  │
│ 12399                                                                         │
│ 12400 If the operands are integer vectors, then they are compared element by  │
│ 12401 element. The result is an ``i1`` vector with the same number of         │
│ elements                                                                      │
│ 12402 as the values being compared. Otherwise, the result is an ``i1``.       │
│ 12403                                                                         │
│ 12404 If the ``samesign`` keyword is present and the operands are not of the  │
│ 12405 same sign then the result is a :ref:`poison value <poisonvalues>`.      │
│ 12406                                                                         │
│ 12407 Example:                                                                │
│ 12408 """"""""                                                                │
│ 12409                                                                         │
│ 12410 .. code-block:: text                                                    │
│ 12411                                                                         │
│ 12412       <result> = icmp eq i32 4, 5          ; yields: result=false       │
│ 12413       <result> = icmp ne ptr %X, %X        ; yields: result=false       │
│ 12414       <result> = icmp ult i16  4, 5        ; yields: result=true        │
│ 12415       <result> = icmp sgt i16  4, 5        ; yields: result=false       │
│ 12416       <result> = icmp ule i16 -4, 5        ; yields: result=false       │
│ 12417       <result> = icmp sge i16  4, 5        ; yields: result=false       │
│ 12418                                                                         │
│ 12419 .. _i_fcmp:                                                             │
│ 12420                                                                         │
│ 12421 '``fcmp``' Instruction                                                  │
│ 12422 ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^                                                  │
│ 12423                                                                         │
│ 12424 Syntax:                                                                 │
│ 12425 """""""                                                                 │
│ 12426                                                                         │
│ 12427 ::                                                                      │
│ 12428                                                                         │
│ 12429       <result> = fcmp [fast-math flags]* <cond> <ty> <op1>, <op2>     ; │
│ yields i1 or <N x i1>:result                                                  │
│ 12430                                                                         │
│ 12431 Overview:                                                               │
│ 12432 """""""""                                                               │
│ 12433                                                                         │
│ 12434 The '``fcmp``' instruction returns a boolean value or vector of boolean │
│ 12435 values based on comparison of its operands.                             │
│ 12436                                                                         │
│ 12437 If the operands are floating-point scalars, then the result type is a   │
│ 12438 boolean (:ref:`i1 <t_integer>`).                                        │
│ 12439                                                                         │
│ 12440 If the operands are floating-point vectors, then the result type is a   │
│ 12441 vector of boolean with the same number of elements as the operands      │
│ being                                                                         │
│ 12442 compared.                                                               │
│ 12443                                                                         │
│ 12444 Arguments:                                                              │
│ 12445 """"""""""                                                              │
│ 12446                                                                         │
│ 12447 The '``fcmp``' instruction takes three operands. The first operand is   │
│ 12448 the condition code indicating the kind of comparison to perform. It is  │
│ 12449 not a value, just a keyword. The possible condition codes are:          │
│ 12450                                                                         │
│ 12451 #. ``false``: no comparison, always returns false                       │
│ 12452 #. ``oeq``: ordered and equal                                           │
│ 12453 #. ``ogt``: ordered and greater than                                    │
│ 12454 #. ``oge``: ordered and greater than or equal                           │
│ 12455 #. ``olt``: ordered and less than                                       │
│ 12456 #. ``ole``: ordered and less than or equal                              │
│ 12457 #. ``one``: ordered and not equal                                       │
│ 12458 #. ``ord``: ordered (no nans)                                           │
│ 12459 #. ``ueq``: unordered or equal                                          │
│ 12460 #. ``ugt``: unordered or greater than                                   │
│ 12461 #. ``uge``: unordered or greater than or equal                          │
│ 12462 #. ``ult``: unordered or less than                                      │
│ 12463 #. ``ule``: unordered or less than or equal                             │
│ 12464 #. ``une``: unordered or not equal                                      │
│ 12465 #. ``uno``: unordered (either nans)                                     │
│ 12466 #. ``true``: no comparison, always returns true                         │
│ 12467                                                                         │
│ 12468 *Ordered* means that neither operand is a QNAN while *unordered* means  │
│ 12469 that either operand may be a QNAN.                                      │
│ 12470                                                                         │
│ 12471 Each of ``val1`` and ``val2`` arguments must be either a                │
│ :ref:`floating-point                                                          │
│ 12472 <t_floating>` type or a :ref:`vector <t_vector>` of floating-point      │
│ type.                                                                         │
│ 12473 They must have identical types.                                         │
│ 12474                                                                         │
│ 12475 Semantics:                                                              │
│ 12476 """"""""""                                                              │
│ 12477                                                                         │
│ 12478 The '``fcmp``' instruction compares ``op1`` and ``op2`` according to    │
│ the                                                                           │
│ 12479 condition code given as ``cond``. If the operands are vectors, then the │
│ 12480 vectors are compared element by element. Each comparison performed      │
│ 12481 always yields an :ref:`i1 <t_integer>` result, as follows:              │
│ 12482                                                                         │
│ 12483 #. ``false``: always yields ``false``, regardless of operands.          │
│ 12484 #. ``oeq``: yields ``true`` if both operands are not a QNAN and ``op1`` │
│ 12485    is equal to ``op2``.                                                 │
│ 12486 #. ``ogt``: yields ``true`` if both operands are not a QNAN and ``op1`` │
│ 12487    is greater than ``op2``.                                             │
│ 12488 #. ``oge``: yields ``true`` if both operands are not a QNAN and ``op1`` │
│ 12489    is greater than or equal to ``op2``.                                 │
│ 12490 #. ``olt``: yields ``true`` if both operands are not a QNAN and ``op1`` │
│ 12491    is less than ``op2``.                                                │
│ 12492 #. ``ole``: yields ``true`` if both operands are not a QNAN and ``op1`` │
│ 12493    is less than or equal to ``op2``.                                    │
│ 12494 #. ``one``: yields ``true`` if both operands are not a QNAN and ``op1`` │
│ 12495    is not equal to ``op2``.                                             │
│ 12496 #. ``ord``: yields ``true`` if both operands are not a QNAN.            │
│ 12497 #. ``ueq``: yields ``true`` if either operand is a QNAN or ``op1`` is   │
│ 12498    equal to ``op2``.                                                    │
│ 12499 #. ``ugt``: yields ``true`` if either operand is a QNAN or ``op1`` is   │
│ 12500    greater than ``op2``.                                                │
│ 12501 #. ``uge``: yields ``true`` if either operand is a QNAN or ``op1`` is   │
│ 12502    greater than or equal to ``op2``.                                    │
│ 12503 #. ``ult``: yields ``true`` if either operand is a QNAN or ``op1`` is   │
│ 12504    less than ``op2``.                                                   │
│ 12505 #. ``ule``: yields ``true`` if either operand is a QNAN or ``op1`` is   │
│ 12506    less than or equal to ``op2``.                                       │
│ 12507 #. ``une``: yields ``true`` if either operand is a QNAN or ``op1`` is   │
│ 12508    not equal to ``op2``.                                                │
│ 12509 #. ``uno``: yields ``true`` if either operand is a QNAN.                │
│ 12510 #. ``true``: always yields ``true``, regardless of operands.            │
│ 12511                                                                         │
│ 12512 The ``fcmp`` instruction can also optionally take any number of         │
│ 12513 :ref:`fast-math flags <fastmath>`, which are optimization hints to      │
│ enable                                                                        │
│ 12514 otherwise unsafe floating-point optimizations.                          │
│ 12515                                                                         │
│ 12516 Any set of fast-math flags are legal on an ``fcmp`` instruction, but    │
│ the                                                                           │
│ 12517 only flags that have any effect on its semantics are those that allow   │
│ 12518 assumptions to be made about the values of input arguments; namely      │
│ 12519 ``nnan``, ``ninf``, and ``reassoc``. See :ref:`fastmath` for more       │
│ information.                                                                  │
│ 12520                                                                         │
│ 12521 Example:                                                                │
│ 12522 """"""""                                                                │
│ 12523                                                                         │
│ 12524 .. code-block:: text                                                    │
│ 12525                                                                         │
│ 12526       <result> = fcmp oeq float 4.0, 5.0    ; yields: result=false      │
│ 12527       <result> = fcmp one float 4.0, 5.0    ; yields: result=true       │
│ 12528       <result> = fcmp olt float 4.0, 5.0    ; yields: result=true       │
│ 12529       <result> = fcmp ueq double 1.0, 2.0   ; yields: result=false      │
│ 12530                                                                         │
│ 12531 .. _i_phi:                                                              │
│ 12532                                                                         │
│ 12533 '``phi``' Instruction                                                   │
│ 12534 ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^                                                   │
│ 12535                                                                         │
│ 12536 Syntax:                                                                 │
│ 12537 """""""                                                                 │
│ 12538                                                                         │
│ 12539 ::                                                                      │
│ 12540                                                                         │
│ 12541       <result> = phi [fast-math-flags] <ty> [ <val0>, <label0>], ...    │
│ 12542                                                                         │
│ 12543 Overview:                                                               │
│ 12544 """""""""                                                               │
│ 12545                                                                         │
│ 12546 The '``phi``' instruction is used to implement the φ node in the SSA    │
│ 12547 graph representing the function.                                        │
│ 12548                                                                         │
│ 12549 Arguments:                                                              │
│ 12550 """"""""""                                                              │
│ 12551                                                                         │
│ 12552 The type of the incoming values is specified with the first type field. │
│ 12553 After this, the '``phi``' instruction takes a list of pairs as          │
│ 12554 arguments, with one pair for each predecessor basic block of the        │
│ current                                                                       │
│ 12555 block. Only values of :ref:`first class <t_firstclass>` type may be     │
│ used as                                                                       │
│ 12556 the value arguments to the PHI node. Only labels may be used as the     │
│ 12557 label arguments.                                                        │
│ 12558                                                                         │
│ 12559 There must be no non-phi instructions between the start of a basic      │
│ block                                                                         │
│ 12560 and the PHI instructions: i.e. PHI instructions must be first in a      │
│ basic                                                                         │
│ 12561 block.                                                                  │
│ 12562                                                                         │
│ 12563 For the purposes of the SSA form, the use of each incoming value is     │
│ 12564 deemed to occur on the edge from the corresponding predecessor block to │
│ 12565 the current block (but after any definition of an '``invoke``'          │
│ 12566 instruction's return value on the same edge).                           │
│ 12567                                                                         │
│ 12568 The optional ``fast-math-flags`` marker indicates that the phi has one  │
│ 12569 or more :ref:`fast-math-flags <fastmath>`. These are optimization hints │
│ ---------------------------------------                                       │
